🏥 Centralized Smart Triage Backend

This is the Node.js backend for the Smart Medical Triage system. It acts as the central hub that receives patient history and camera-based vitals, 
merges them in an in-memory "Waiting Room," checks for clinical red flags, and uses Google Gemini AI to summarize the patient's triage zone. 
All data is securely stored in a local SQLite database.

⚙️ Prerequisites

Before you begin, make sure you have the following installed on your computer:
Node.js (v16 or higher recommended)
npm (Node Package Manager, which comes installed with Node.js)

🚀 How to Install and Run Locally

1. Download the Code
Clone this repository to your local machine or download the ZIP file and extract it.

2. Install Dependencies
Open your terminal (or command prompt), navigate to the folder where you saved this code, and run:

npm install

This will automatically read the `package.json` file and create the `node_modules` folder specifically for your computer. 

3. Set Up Your Environment Variables
You must provide your own Google Gemini API key for the AI pipeline to work. 
* Create a new text file in the root folder and name it exactly `.env`
* Open the `.env` file and paste the following line, replacing the placeholder with your actual key:

GOOGLE_API_KEY=your_actual_api_key_here

Save the file. 

4. Start the Server
In your terminal, run the following command:

node server.js


If everything is set up correctly, you will see this in your terminal:
> 🗄️ Connected to Central Database!
> 🚀 Smart Server is running!
> 🔗 Click to view database logic: http://localhost:3000/api/view
> 🏥 Backend is ready to receive data on port 3000

📡 API Endpoints

Once the server is running, the following routes are active:

`POST /api/sync/history`** Receives JSON payloads. Automatically places patients in the buffer ("Waiting Room") until both history and vitals are received, then runs the AI triage pipeline.
`GET /api/view`** Returns all processed patient records currently saved in the SQLite database as a JSON array.
`GET /api/status`** Provides live server health metrics, memory usage, and lists the IDs of patients currently sitting in the Waiting Room.

🗄️ Database Notes
You do not need to install a database software right now. 
This app uses sqlite3. When you start the server for the first time, 
it will automatically create a file named patient_data.sqlite in your folder to store the data locally.
